<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 94 / RJB offered Pounds 914m in bidding to win British Coal
regions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RJB Mining, the coal company, put in an offer of Pounds 914m to win the
government's backing as preferred bidder for the English regions of British
Coal, it emerged yesterday.
In one of the boldest and most controversial fund-raising exercises in
recent times on the London Stock Exchange, RJB aims to raise Pounds 425m in
a share issue and Pounds 628m as debt.
In presentations to potential investors, RJB and its adviser, Barclays de
Zoete Wedd, indicate that they believe the debt can be cleared by 1998 when
existing electricity contracts end.
RJB predicts annual pretax profits of Pounds 220m by the turn of the century
on turnover of Pounds 1.24bn. Profits before then will be Pounds 116m in
1995, Pounds 188m in 1996, Pounds 211m in 1997 and Pounds 186m in 1998.
The amount of money RJB, capitalised at Pounds 157m, needs to raise means
that investors will study its projections closely. Many executives in the
electricity and coal industries believe the company, which bid more than 50
per cent higher than the nearest rival, is taking a highly optimistic view
of markets, particularly after 1998.
RJB says in its presentation, copies of which have been obtained by the
Financial Times, that it expects to sell about 34m tonnes of coal from the
regions it is acquiring and sell it at an average of Pounds 1.32 a gigajoule
at today's prices.
Some analysts believe sales around the mid-20m tonne mark are more
realistic. The generators, to which most of the coal will be sold, are
thought to want to buy coal for nearer Pounds 1 a gigajoule and are prepared
to import rather than pay what they believe to be excessive UK prices.
Among other key aspects of the presentation, RJB says:
Costs per tonne can be cut by at least 10 per cent, partly through
streamlining colliery management and increasing equipment utilisation.
The English electricity supply market will require 27.1m-43m tonnes a year
at the turn of the century.
Of the Pounds 628m it plans to borrow, Pounds 528m will be through bank debt
and Pounds 100m through corporate bonds.
Net assets of the regions being bought are Pounds 902m and projected
operating cash flow over five years is Pounds 1.35bn.
Expected dividend yield is 4.5 per cent initially, with a policy of rapid
dividend growth after the debt is cleared.
Some 95 per cent of shares will be placed with institutions, with 5 per cent
set aside for an offer for sale, although this could rise to 15 per cent if
there is demand.
RJB yesterday refused to comment.
</TEXT>
