<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 94 / Dublin coalition set to fall as Spring resigns
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The collapse of Ireland's coalition government seemed inevitable last night
as Mr Dick Spring, the Labour leader, announced his resignation as deputy
prime minister. He said the other five Labour party ministers would also
quit the Fianna Fail-led government.
Mr Spring's decision came at the end of a day of high political drama in
which Mr Albert Rey-nolds, the Irish prime minster, in a last-ditch act of
political contrition aimed at regaining Labour support, had conceded his
mistake in the appointment of Mr Harry Whelehan, the attorney-general, to be
president of the High Court.
Mr Whelehan has been under fire for his department's failure to act for
seven months on a request from Northern Ireland for the extradition of a
priest later convicted of child sex abuse.
Mr Reynolds last night seemed certain to go to President Mary Robinson to
seek an early dissolution of parliament and an early general election.
However, there was growing speculation that the president would use her
powers under the constitution to force the parties to create a new coalition
within the existing parliament.
One factor is likely to be a wish to do as little damage to the Northern
Ireland peace process as possible.
After a day of high farce rich in rumour, Dublin was in sombre mood last
night as Mr Reynolds struggled to save his political career. In a 45-minute
address to the Dail, the Irish parliament,
Mr Reynolds offered what he called the 'full facts, the unvarnished facts'
on the extradition case.
He said he acted unwisely in the attorney-general's appointment.
With opposition MPs threatening to reveal new evidence to 'rock the
foundations of the state', it was not until 6.45 that Mr Spring, the
architect of the crisis, rose to speak for the first time in the drama.
After three separate adjournments the Dail, the Irish parliament, was in its
fourth sitting when Mr Reynolds conceded his error in the attorney-general's
appointment.
Amid speculation of a document showing official interference to block the
extradition of the paedophile priest, Mr Reynolds reported that he had
contacted all members of the attorney-general's office except two who are
out of the country. Unionists reassured, Page 9; Editorial comment, Page 21
