<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 94 / International Company News: Kidder disposes of mortgage
bonds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Kidder Peabody, the US investment bank, has disposed of a large part of its
portfolio of complex mortgage-backed bonds. It said yesterday it had hired
an outside firm to advise on the 'management and orderly disposition' of the
rest.
The bond sales mark a reversal of a plan announced in early October to
transfer the bond holdings to GE Capital, another part of the General
Electric group. Since then, General Electric has agreed to sell the bulk of
Kidder's operations to another broking firm, PaineWebber.
Kidder said yesterday its holdings of the securities, known as
collateralised mortgage obligations (CMOs), now stood at Dollars 4bn, down
from Dollars 6.7bn at the end of October. In March, before the company began
its sales, the portfolio was valued at Dollars 16bn.
CMOs are complex derivative-type securities created from pools of
mortgage-backed bonds. They have generally performed worse than other bonds
as fixed-income markets have retreated this year.
Kidder, which said it had hired New York-based investment firm BlackRock
Financial Management to advise on the remainder of the portfolio, yesterday
tried to play down suggestions of a fire-sale. It said it 'plans to continue
to own and manage the portfolio for the foreseeable future, and has no
current plans to immediately dispose of all or any significant part of the
portfolio'.
Fears that Kidder would try to unload the rest of its holdings have helped
to hold back prices in the CMO market for some months.
</TEXT>
