<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow volatile in wake of rate
increase
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA BRANSTEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US shares reacted wildly to the Federal Reserve's announcement yesterday
afternoon that it would raise the Federal Funds target rate by 75 basis
points to 5 1/2 per cent, writes Lisa Bransten in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 3.37 at 3,826.36. The
more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 lost 1.01 at 465.03, while the
American Stock Exchange composite was 0.11 easier at 448.61 and the Nasdaq
composite 0.88 firmer at 769.02. Trading volume on the New York SE was 340m
shares.
Immediately after the Fed's announcement, the Dow shot up more than 23
points on the heels of a rallying bond market. But the index dropped
substantially as the long bond returned to its pre-announcement level, the
Dow falling 21 points before rebounding somewhat.
A broad consensus of economists expected an increase of about 50 basis
points, to 5 1/4 per cent, so the Fed's move caught some off guard.
Interest rate increases are generally bad for the markets, because they
deter corporate borrowing. Some economists attributed falling share prices
to signals from the Fed that it might move to raise the interest rate target
again in the near term. 'Today's tightening is hardly going to represent the
definitive end,' said Mr John Lipsky, chief economist at Salomon Brothers.
Share prices were mixed among the banks, which tend to be particularly
sensitive to interest rate changes. Gainers included Chemical Banking,
Dollars  1/8 up at Dollars 36 1/2 , and Chase Manhattan, Dollars  1/2 ahead
at Dollars 36 3/4 . Declining were NationsBank, down Dollars  1/4 at Dollars
47 3/4 , and BankAmerica, Dollars  1/8 lower at Dollars 42 1/4 .
Microsoft, the software maker, saw its shares increase Dollars  1/8 to
Dollars 64 5/8 on news that it would launch a new, on-line service to be
available in 35 countries. Digital Equipment was up Dollars 1 at Dollars 33
5/8 on news that it would manage the client/server network for Microsoft.
ADRs of British Telecommunications, which will help carry the new service,
closed unchanged at Dollars 61 3/8 .
Whirlpool increased by Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 53 after announcing that it
would streamline operations by cutting 3,200 jobs in its European and North
American operations and closing two North American plants.
Two retailers gained ground on reports of strong third-quarter earnings.
Home Depot put on Dollars  1/4 at Dollars 47 3/4 and JC Penney Dollars  7/8
at Dollars 47 3/4 . Dayton Hudson dropped Dollars 3 3/8 to Dollars 80 5/8 in
spite of a strong earnings report.
Canada
Toronto stocks finished softer after early strong gains were wiped out by
the US interest rates rise, and traders said they expected choppy trade to
continue.
The TSE 300 index shed 8.29 points on the day at 4,168.90 after putting on
more than 20 points initially. An analyst said investors either had to step
outside the market (yesterday) or be strapped in and have a very strong
stomach.
Volume totalled a moderate 59m shares valued at CDollars 698.5m and
declining stocks outscored rises by 471 to 266.
Among interest rate-sensitive issues, the real estate sector was hardest
hit, sinking 46.05 to 2,152.66. Another seven of the 14 sub-group indices
fell, including transport, down 47.19 to 4,495.18. Golds lost 24.15 at
9,679.98 in spite of higher bullion prices.
Newbridge Networks climbed CDollars 2 1/4 to CDollars 46 3/4 after Merrill
Lynch upgraded its rating on the stock to near-term above average.
Vitran jumped CDollars 1 1/8 to CDollars 9 on news that it has acquired a US
freight carrier, the Overland Group of Companies, doubling the size of the
company.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
