<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 94 / Markets Report: Fed lifts US short-term rates by 75 basis
points
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Federal Reserve yesterday raised US short-term interest rates by 75
basis points, the sixth monetary tightening this year, writes Philip Gawith.
In a move described by analysts as the most widely expected interest rate
increase in history, the Fed lifted the Federal Funds rate to 5.5 per cent,
from 4.75 per cent, and the discount rate to 4.75 per cent, from 4 per cent.
The dollar gained a pfennig on the news, standing at DM1.5558, from DM1.5445
before the Fed's announcement, at the New York close. Against the yen it had
reached Y98.75, from Y98.2. The Fed's move came around 19.30 GMT.
Analysts described the dollar's response as fairly muted, reflecting the
fact that higher interest rates had already been discounted in the market.
The increase was slightly more than traders had expected, with most
participants expecting the Federal Funds rate to rise by 50 basis points.
Mr Carl Weinberg, chief economist at High Frequency Economics in New York,
said the statement which accompanied the move had been entirely
non-committal about whether a further tightening of policy could be expected
next month. He said there was an 'innuendo' in the decision to raise rates
by 75 basis points, which suggested that the Fed might wish to avoid another
move in 1994. Futures markets were discounting short-term rates rising to
around 6 per cent by the year-end.
Although US interest rates have now risen above those in Germany, Mr
Weinberg said the problem for the dollar remained huge capital outflows. He
said a rally in the dollar required that economic growth slow below 3 per
cent, and that there be no signs of inflationary pressure. This combination,
he added, did not look to be at hand. 'We are at least a quarter or more
away from any possible remission period for the dollar.'
As to the short-term outlook. looking back at previous Fed tightenings this
year, Mr Brian Durrant, economist at broker GNI in London, noted that
Dollars /DM typically jumps 0.75 to 1 pfennig on the news, but subsequently
surrenders these gains within three days.
The Irish punt has shown some weakness in recent days, as uncertainty about
the survival of the ruling coalition has raised the prospect of an early
general election. The punt closed at IPounds 1.0187 against sterling, from
IPounds 1.0189. For the past few months it had traded in the IPounds 1.01 to
IPounds 1.013 range.
But Mr Jim Power, senior economist at the Bank of Ireland in Dublin, said
concerns about political instability were 'totally overdone'. Although
elections were by no means assured, Mr Power said that even if there were to
be a new government, 'we can be guaranteed that economic policy will be
virtually identical to what we have had so far'.
He said no politician would have the nerve to challenge the economic policy
consensus, which was 'largely dictated by the Maastricht convergence
criteria'.
Although the punt and sterling track each other closely, Mr Power said the
recent decline in sterling had not been a factor in the weaker punt. Rather,
this reflected the political uncertainty, and the fact that interest rate
differentials across the yield curve had moved too much in favour of
sterling.
The Swedish krona slipped back towards the level it was at before the Sunday
referendum, which voted in favour of joining the EU. After rising towards
SKr4.65, from SKr4.75, against the D-Mark in the first bout of
post-election, the krona has since given back most of its gains. It closed
in London at SKr4.736, from SKr4.712.
The French franc recovered some of its recent loss to end at FFr3.437/D-Mark
from FFr3.440. Mr Malcolm Barr, international economist at Chemical Bank in
London, said recent franc weakness, on alleged uncertainty surrounding next
year's presidential elections, had been exaggerated. 'Even a Delors victory
does not have much policy implication,' said Mr Barr. From a financial
market perspective, he said, there was little to choose between the likely
candidates.
In its daily activities the Bank of England cleared, at established rates, a
Pounds 500m shortage in UK money markets. Overnight money traded between 3
3/4 and 5 per cent.
Sterling weakened slightly against the D-Mark and the dollar, finishing at
Dollars 1.5826, from Dollars 1.5849 against the latter. It has now fallen
nearly 4 per cent from a high around Dollars 1.64 at the beginning of the
month.
</TEXT>
