<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 94 / International Capital Markets: Tokyo SE eases rules for
foreign company listings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GERARD BAKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Tokyo Stock Exchange yesterday announced a series of measures designed
to make Japan's lacklustre stock market more attractive to foreign
companies.
Mr Mitsuhide Yamaguchi, president of the exchange, said the proposed new
rules, which could take effect as early as next January, were aimed at
removing the principal obstacles to a Tokyo listing, especially for Asian
companies.
During the last year a succession of Chinese enterprises have listed on the
Hong Kong and New York stock markets where the rules are much less rigid.
The Tokyo reforms are aimed specifically at private, former state
enterprises of China and other Asian countries.
Mr Yamaguchi said he expected the changes to pave the way for more than 200
Chinese and east Asian companies to join the exchange in the next few years.
The easing of listing requirements means the current stipulation that
companies must be listed on their own national stock exchange before
receiving a Japanese listing will be scrapped, as will the rule requiring a
minimum one-year moratorium after a privatisation.
The minimum asset requirement for companies wishing to have their shares
traded in Tokyo will be cut to Y10bn (Dollars 102.6m) from Y100bn. Also, a
stipulation that companies have at least three years' annual profits of Y20m
is being changed to a requirement of profits averaging Y2m over the three
years before a listing. Companies will also no longer have to have a minimum
of 10,000 shareholders.
The new rules are expected to be approved by the exchange's governing body
next month, and could be in place by January.
Foreign companies in Tokyo yesterday welcomed the measures. 'There is no
question that privatised businesses in emerging markets desperately need
access to a highly liquid market if they are to realise their potential
growth,' the chief executive of one large financial institution said. 'These
measures will facilitate that.'
However, the changes are not expected to improve prospects much for
companies already listed in Tokyo.
In the last year, at least seven overseas companies, including most
recently, British Gas, have announced plans to delist from the TSE. The
total number of foreign shares listed on the exchange has fallen from 127 in
1991 to fewer than 100 today.
Most companies that have left Tokyo in the last year have complained of the
collapse in share-trading volumes and exorbitant trading commissions.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
