<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 94 / UK Company News: CE Heath hit by direct line costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The cost of entering the direct line insurance business and accounting
vagaries at an Australian associate depressed profits at CE Heath for the
six months to the end of September.
The pre-tax figure fell from Pounds 14.9m - inflated by a Pounds 3.25m
exceptional item - to Pounds 6.37m. Turnover on continuing operations was
little changed at Pounds 81.5m (Pounds 81.5m).
Heath's Premium Search telephone broking business incurred losses of Pounds
1.6m during its first four months of operation, with Mr Peter Presland,
chief executive, forecasting that the full-year deficit would be about
Pounds 4m. He anticipated that the business, which is likely to employ up to
400 people, would move into profit in 1996.
Mr Presland denied that the company had left it too late to enter the direct
line market. 'There is a big market out there for this kind of service and
it is going to get bigger as more and more people look for their insurance
needs away from the high street.'
CE Heath International Holdings, the group's Australian associate in which
it holds a 23 per cent stake, saw its profit contribution drop from Pounds
6m to Pounds 1.2m. The company blamed the fall on the halving of its stake,
and Australian accounting rules which make the company reflect all
investment gains and losses in its profit and loss account.
Losses from the New York underwriting business widened from Pounds 450,000
to nearly Pounds 1m, although the company added that the subsidiary's book
of agricultural business had been sold and the losses would not recur.
Profits from the computing services division rose 26 per cent to Pounds 2.7m
(Pounds 2.14m).
Earnings per share dropped 46 per cent to 5.9p (10.9p). The interim dividend
is maintained at 5p. The shares rose 13p to 232p.
COMMENT
Heath's chunky dividend, currently yielding nearly 9 per cent, should limit
any downside for the shares. However, in the short-term it is difficult to
see where any sustained earnings growth is likely to come from. With its
broking operations under pressure, underwriting contributions declining and
the direct line service in its formative stages, it is only the fairly
limited contribution from computer services which can be counted on. Worth
holding for the yield, and on the off-chance a predator might swing into
view.
</TEXT>
