<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 94 / UK Company News: Hydro gets Pounds 10.5m value from placing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER PEARSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The placing shares in Hydro International, which is coming to market, have
been priced at 80p, valuing the maker of control systems for storm water
control and sewage separation at about Pounds 10.5m.
Some 4.63m shares are being placed by Allied Provincial Securities. Of
these, 4m are new and the balance are being sold by Mr Tim Lamb and Mr Bob
Smisson, founding directors and chief executive and deputy chairman
respectively.
Mr Lamb and Mr Smisson are being paid dividends totalling Pounds 200,000,
conditional on the listing. The board does not intend to declare a dividend
for the year to December 31: subsequently a dividend policy will be
introduced 'broadly reflecting growth in the group's underlying profit'.
Of the Pounds 2.75m raised in the placing, some Pounds 2.3m is to be used
marketing Hydro's products, investing in information technology,
constructing a further test facility, and recruiting additional staff,
particularly in research and development.
Mrs Elizabeth Kennedy, a director in Allied Provincial's corporate finance
department, said that Hydro was a development type company, though not a
'blue sky' company, in that it has patented products bringing in revenue and
profit. In 1993 it made Pounds 156,000 on Pounds 4.1m turnover and in the
six months to June 30, profits were Pounds 154,000 on Pounds 2.4m turnover.
She said that the pricing therefore fell between what the company thought it
was worth and what the institutions were prepared to pay. Ten 'mainline'
institutions have taken shares, including Scottish Amicable, Friends
Provident and Legal &amp; General.
Mrs Kennedy said Dollars 3.7m (Pounds 2.25m) orders from Columbus, Georgia,
had acted as one of the triggers behind Hydro's decision to come to market.
</TEXT>
