<PROFILE>_AN-EKPEKAEHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941116
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 94 / MAM calls halt to accepting 'soft commissions'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mercury Asset Management, the UK's largest fund management company, has
decided that from next January it will no longer accept 'soft commissions' -
free goods or services - from brokers it agrees to channel business through
around the world.
MAM's move comes as regulators in the US, UK and Hong Kong are scrutinising
the rules on soft commissions out of concern they can lead to a subtle form
of bribery which harms the interests of the clients on whose behalf funds
are managed.
Fund managers may pay more for securities than they ought to in order to
generate the agreed level of business.
In the UK, the move is likely to heighten pressure on MAM's competitors to
adopt a similar stance as pension fund clients seek greater transparency in
fees they pay to their fund managers.
'We have seen and very much felt the move towards clean fees,' said Mr Colin
Clark, marketing director at MAM. He said that MAM has taken a tough line on
soft commission for several years and that the value of services which they
receive under soft commission arrangements is 'under Pounds 2m' per year.
Imro, the UK self-regulatory body for the fund management industry, has
recently issued a discussion document which proposes restricting the types
of goods and services which fund managers can accept under soft commission
arrangements.
'Regulators internationally have felt there was scope for abuse around the
boundaries,' said Mr Robin Clark, director of monitoring at Imro. 'It is one
thing to accept (soft commissions) for research and another for travel to
warm sunny climates,' he said. Earlier this year, Imro fined a division of
Abbey Life for allowing its fund managers to accept free travel to the US
and Asia under soft commission arrangements. Under soft commission
arrangements, brokers agree to the provision of such things as research,
performance measurement services, Reuters or Bloomberg screens in exchange
for a fund manager's guarantee that a minimum amount of business will be
executed through the firm. Soft commission services are typically those
which fund managers would normally have to pay for out of their own pocket.
It would be considered an abuse to use soft commissions to pay for office
furniture, rent or entertainment expenses.
Imro intends to issue guidelines banning fund managers from accepting
certain goods and services paid for by commissions with strings attached.
In Hong Kong, where the use of soft commissions is widespread, the
Securities and Futures Authority has provoked outcry among the broking
community by announcing it would undertake a similar review of soft
commission arrangements. The US has recently increased disclosure
requirements for mutual fund managers who accept services with strings
attached and is under pressure to do more.
A difficulty is enforcing restrictions on foreign business.
</TEXT>
