FT  16 NOV 94 / 'Sleaze' judge refuses to be swayed by PM's views
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lord Nolan, the judge heading the committee of inquiry into standards of
conduct in public life, has made clear that he will not be swayed by the
prime minister's view that MPs should continue to have the right to enjoy
outside business interests.
As the government tries to recover from allegations of 'sleaze' against
senior Tory MPs, Lord Nolan has said that Mr John Major's views on this are
to be regarded as a personal expression which stand alongside those of any
MP.
Mr Major said in his Mansion House speech on Monday night that parliament
emphasised that Britain 'would not benefit from a monastic Commons' and that
politicians 'must know how this world works'.
Lord Nolan is understood to have told committee members that Mr Major's
views should not sway their examination of whether MPs should have business
interests.
He has not ruled out the possibility that the prime minister could be
summoned to give evidence to the committee.
The Nolan committee agreed yesterday to produce an interim report into its
activities before the end of the year. The committee is examining written
submissions from members of the public.
Lord Nolan also agreed to set up three separate sub-committees to examine
the activities of MPs, the ability of ministers and civil servants to move
to private companies, and appointments to quangos.
Mr Tom King, the former Northern Ireland secretary, is among the three
committee members examining whether former ministers can move to the private
sector, in spite of his declaration in the register of members' interests of
directorships.
Lord Nolan is understood to believe that there is no conflict of interest in
this.
</TEXT>
