<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 94 / Building societies' body urges rights for borrowers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
About 7m people who have mortgages with building societies would be given
new rights to vote on issues affecting societies if proposals put forward by
the sector's trade association are accepted by the government.
The Building Societies Association, responding to a consultation paper from
the Treasury which marked the second stage in its review of societies'
powers, said that borrowers should have voting rights like investing
members.
But it dismissed two key suggestions made by the Treasury for making
societies more accountable. These were the setting up of consultative
committees of members and requiring societies to reserve some board places
for candidates nominated by 'ordinary members'.
As mutual institutions, societies are owned by their customers who are
members, rather than being responsible to shareholders.
The debate on what wider powers societies should be given to enable them to
compete more effectively in the retail financial services sector has focused
attention on how far in practice members can hold societies to account and
whether this form of ownership gives them an unfair advantage.
The association says that societies should give members more information, in
an accessible form, about their role as members rather than simply as
customers. To encourage this the association plans to issue guidance to
societies and a leaflet for general distribution.
It says that putting members in a better position to exercise their
membership rights would balance giving societies the wider and more flexible
powers it strongly supports.
</TEXT>
