<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 94 / Plea on livestock granted
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Exporters of veal calves yesterday won permission to bring an early High
Court challenge to a ban on using Coventry airport to fly livestock to the
Continent.
Phoenix Aviation and CC Freight, a consortium of farmers and cattle dealers,
said they were given permission to use the airport this month. But the
Labour-led city council, which owns the airport and has come under pressure
from animal rights activists, said no decision had been taken and it was
entitled to suspend flights.
Sir Christopher Prout QC, for Phoenix and CC Freight, told the High Court
that farmers faced losing long-established Continental markets.
He told Mr Justice Tucker the trade had been hit by the refusal of ferries
to ship live animals. Sir Christopher asked for leave to seek judicial
review on the grounds that the council had acted unlawfully and
unreasonably.
Mr Stuart Isaacs, for the council, said no decision had been taken on the
transportation of veal calves from the airport, and the council was still
considering the issue.
Mr Justice Tucker ordered that a full court hearing be expedited and
extended an injunction allowing Phoenix to continue the flights pending the
High Court's ruling.
Ferrylink Freight Service has halted livestock shipments to the Continent
after taking one such shipment from Sheerness, Kent, to the Netherlands last
week.
