<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 94 / Power use rise shows economic growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Evidence of economic growth strengthened yesterday when PowerGen, the power
generator, said overall demand for electricity in England and Wales rose 3
per cent in the six months to October after three years of stagnation.
The company, reporting a 9 per cent rise in pre-tax profits to Pounds 118m,
said the growth in demand was 'due to increased consumption in the
industrial and commercial sectors, indicating a general upturn in economic
activity'.
The increase compares with current annual growth forecasts in the National
Grid's seven-year statement of 1.3 per cent.
In the six months to the end of September electricity demand was 123.3
terrawatt hours, against 119.7 in the comparable six months of last year and
1992, 119.9 in 1991 and 118.9 in 1990.
The precise correlation between growth in electricity demand and economic
growth is debatable but a rough rule of thumb in the industry is that power
demand growth is usually about two-thirds of the expansion in gross domestic
product.
Offer, the electricity industry regulator, yesterday announced the terms of
reference for a Monopolies and Mergers Commission inquiry into Scottish
Hydro-Electric's controls, but said it had no plans to reconsider price
controls for the sector.
It said it was working on licence amendments arising from changes in
controls on Scottish Power and the 12 regional electricity companies in
England and Wales. It expected to publish the changes in the next few weeks.
Professor Stephen Littlechild, director-general of Offer, said he had asked
the monopolies commission to report within six months on the distribution
and supply price controls of Hydro-Electric and the 'hydro benefit'
provision which provides for a transfer of revenue from the generation
business to distribution and transmission.
Hydro-Electric was the only company to reject price controls announced this
year by Prof Littlechild to take effect from next April. It was this that
triggered the referral to the commission.
PowerGen dividend up, Page 27
Joint ventures plan, Page 32
</TEXT>
