<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 94 / Abbey National boosts direct line
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Abbey National, the home loans and banking group, is to expand its telephone
finance operation by an extra 250 jobs in the next three years.
Mr Peter Sunderland, director for direct distribution, said customers would
be offered financial services by telephone from March next year. The first
50 jobs would be advertised this week.
The new jobs will be based in Glasgow, where Abbey's life insurance division
is located, and will take the number of Abbey staff in the city to more than
1,500.
The existing Abbey National Direct operation employs 90 people in
Bournemouth and can handle 250,000 telephone calls a year.
Although Abbey has had a telephone operation since 1989, it has focused on
mortgages and related products. This move should allow it to offer a wider
range of life insurance, investment and pensions policies on the telephone.
One area of expansion could be general insurance, when Abbey's joint venture
with Commercial Union, the UK's largest insurance company, starts next year.
The group emphasised, however, that it saw the telephone business as an
extra service for customers rather than as a stand-alone operation.
Abbey's move comes as competition intensifies in telephone banking and
financial services. Last week Direct Line, the telephone insurance company
owned by Royal Bank of Scotland, took a further step towards offering life
insurance when it was accepted by the Personal Investment Authority, the
watchdog to protect the private investor.
</TEXT>
