<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 94 / Fewer high rollers in New York: Rolls-Royce's Manhattan
dealer is closing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Manhattan residents who want a Rolls-Royce will soon have to head, at least
for a time, for unfashionable Long Island - or to suburban New Jersey or
Connecticut - to buy one.
Carriage House Motors, which claims to have been the UK luxury carmaker's
biggest dealer for most of the past decade, closes its doors on Manhattan's
East 61st Street next month. Demand for one of the ultimate car status
symbols is not what it was.
Mr Michael Schudroff, owner of Carriage House and one of the world's biggest
collectors of vintage Rolls-Royces, says: 'People are looking at them
differently these days. The 1990s is not a time to be flamboyant.' So far
this year, Mr Schudroff says he has sold 65 new Rolls-Royces and around 185
'pre-owned' ones. That is a far cry from the late 1980s, when he was selling
around 550 a year, 200 of them new.
The US recession also had something to do with the fall in sales in the
early 1990s, along with a new luxury sales tax which adds 10 per cent to the
price of each vehicle - though many other parts of the US car market have
bounced back in the last two years.
The rising cost of maintaining premises in Manhattan has finally persuaded
Mr Schudroff to move to Greenwich, Connecticut. With smaller premises, he is
preparing to sell a large part of his vintage collection: on December 10,
Sotheby's in New York will auction around 50 vehicles, including cars once
owned by Diana Rigg, David Niven and Bahrain's ruler.
Mr Robert Warren, head of Rolls-Royce's North American business, concedes
the loss of the Manhattan dealer will leave the company unrepresented in an
important market. The company has already been approached by other Manhattan
dealers hoping to be awarded the Rolls-Royce franchise, and he expects to
name a new dealer shortly.
Whoever gets the New York dealership would do well to heed a warning from Mr
Schudroff: 'If you take a car for a test drive, you're lucky if you don't
get whacked by a taxi.'
</TEXT>
