<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 94 / Angola forces sign truce to end civil war
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Angola's government and Unita rebel forces yesterday signed a truce aimed at
halting nearly two decades of civil war.
According to the United Nations the agreement, due to take effect today, is
expected to remain in force until November 22, after which a permanent
ceasefire is to come into force.
The truce was signed as southern African leaders met in Zambia in an urgent
attempt to keep Angola's faltering peace accord on track after a last-minute
postponement of the signing of a formal peace accord, painstakingly
negotiated by United Nations mediators over 11 months.
Mr Thabo Mbeki, South Africa's deputy president, had warned Angolan leaders
that regional countries would take action - widely seen as including
military intervention - should the latest Angolan peace bid crumble.
Under the truce, which represents only part of the formal peace plan and was
signed by top generals of the government and Unita, fighting will halt at
8pm today. A formal peace accord is due to be signed on Sunday. The truce
will remain in effect until the ceasefire called for in the peace accord
takes effect at midnight November 22.
The signing of a formal accord had been delayed because Angola's Unita
rebels refused to sign while government forces were intensifying the war.
The government and Unita initialled the formal pact two weeks ago, but since
then Angolan government army troops overran Unita's stronghold of Huambo in
central Angola.
The Angola war has severely tested the capacity of the southern African
states, which originally came together to help overthow white minority rule
in Rhodesia and South Africa, to act as guarantors of a peace settlement
based on democracy.
If such a regional security pact grouping can succeed in southern Africa, it
could set an example of conflict resolution in other troubled areas of the
continent.
Angola is no different from other African states where an upsurge of
violence has frequently preceded peace agreements.
However the MPLA government may have turned the tables on Mr Jonas Savimbi,
leader of Unita.
Since he rejected his 1992 election defeat, he has tried to win an
ascendancy on the battlefield hoping it would be reflected in the
composition of the government emerging from the Lusaka peace talks. The
MPLA, however, seems to have based its strategy on two more astute
assumptions.
The first was that it could take Huambo. The second was that international
opinion would come down on its side. When Mr Savimbi resorted to war after
his election defeat he lost most of his friends in western capitals.
The MPLA has played a devious game, breaking the spirit of the Lusaka talks,
but Unita's cries of foul play have won little sympathy.
No one underestimates the capacity of Mr Savimbi further to disrupt the
peace process. Even if the signing goes ahead on Sunday formidable obstacles
remain - not least the integration of two rival forces into a national army.
But regional and international developments are putting him under intense
pressure. The prize is peace in a region where the wars for independence
began in the early 1960s. Even the unpredictable Mr Savimbi must realise
knows that sooner or later he has to settle his differences at the
conference table and abide by the result.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
