<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 94 / Economic Watch: W German GDP up 'about 1%'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
West German gross domestic product rose 'about 1 per cent' in the third
quarter, bringing aggregate growth for the first nine months to 2.25 per
cent, the economics ministry said yesterday. Although the recovery now
extended to the whole country and was firmly based, it was still not safe to
say that an extended upswing was assured, the ministry added in its monthly
report on the economy. Rising international interest rates and the marked
strengthening of the D-Mark against the US dollar presented risks to
recovery which made it all the more important for pay negotiators to show
restraint in the 1995 wages round. Final figures are not expected for some
weeks, but the data published yesterday is still in line with previous
government forecasts made just before the federal elections last month.
French non-farm payrolls, excluding the state sector, rose a seasonally
adjusted 58,400, or 0.4 per cent, in the third quarter after a rise of
85,100, or 0.6 per cent, in the second quarter, according to the labour
ministry.
Italy's industrial production grew 4.1 per cent during the first nine months
compared to the same period last year, according to Istat, the national
statistics institute.
