<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 94 / Top aides go in Major's shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major extended the shake-up of his inner circle of advisers
yesterday by announcing that two of the most prominent backroom politicians
in Downing Street would be replaced.
In a further restructuring of the team that will mastermind the Conservative
party's campaign at the next election, the prime minister's office announced
that Mrs Sarah Hogg would stand down as head of the No. 10 Policy Unit.
Mrs Hogg, one of the prime minister's closest aides, has held the post for
four years. But she has recently been strongly criticised by Tory MPs for
some of the prime minister's policy failures.
In addition, Mr Jonathan Hill is leaving his job as political secretary to
the prime minister. He will be replaced by Mr Howell James, a former
director of corporate affairs at the BBC and one-time adviser to Lord Young,
the former trade secretary.
Downing Street emphasised that Mrs Hogg, who has been in charge of the prime
minister's political strategy, was leaving at her own request and had told
Mr Major of her wishes last summer.
Her replacement has not been announced, but senior Tory figures said Mr
Nicholas True, deputy head of the policy unit, was a strong candidate.
The advisers' departure further indicates Mr Major's determination to make a
clean sweep of the top jobs in his kitchen cabinet with little more than two
years until the next election.
Yesterday's moves follow the appointment of Mr Christopher Meyer, a former
diplomat, as press secretary, and of Mr John Ward, the MP for Poole, as his
parliamentary private secretary.
Rightwing Tory MPs did not disguise their pleasure at the departure of Mrs
Hogg, who is regarded as a staunch supporter of European Union integration
and of Britain's ill-fated membership of the exchange rate mechanism. Mrs
Hogg has also been seen as the architect of the prime minister's
unsuccessful 'back to basics' campaign.
However, Mr Major expressed his sadness at her decision to leave. 'Her
staunchness and her wise advice have been of incalculable value,' he said.
Hogg opts for change, Page 9
Observer, Page 25
</TEXT>
